III. That this alſo is a great caſting-downe of the Adverſaries,

 when the Lord, againſt Whom they ſtrive, degrades them, ſmites them in their intellectuals, makes them like a wheele, or, as the Princes of Zoan, fooles, their Counſellours brutiſh 
                  Iſa. 19. 11.: ſo as they ſhall proſecute their own way of ſinne and death, to their own deſtruction; Providentia ab eo tollitur, ne &c. Solv. make their own pit wide, and large, and then fall into it blindfold and headlong; But here the ſober man will ſay;

We muſt not forget now how prayer and praiſe went-out with our Armies, marched along with them, therefore God was with them; nay He was in them in the midſt of them; We muſt tell it out to His praiſe; how God was with His people in the field, how He ſuſtained them there, even more miraculouſly, than Elias, by a Raven; The Ethiopians, the Kings Army (they are Ethiopians unto Me ſayes the Lord Am • s 9. 7.,) theſe were caterers, and purvayers for Gods people; Theſe Ravens, theſe uncleane creatures brought His people meat; So they, the ſervants of the Lord, forced the meate out of thoſe H • rpies clawes, • ate it, and gave praiſe to God: And in the ſtrength of that meate they marched, and their God with them! He gave his people an eye to overlooke all the Lyons and ſhee Beares in their way; He ſtrengthened His people to the battle, gave them power-over their Adverſaries; And brought them home as upon Eagles wings: In all this, prayer commanded God (He is pleaſed ſo to be commanded) and ſo He commanded deliverances for Jacob; They ſhall advance God; In His Name they brake through a Troope: They ſet-up God in His place, and ſo they keep the heart in its place, never out of frame, not afraid with any amazement. Time would fa • le me, if I ſhould ſet downe how prevailing Gods people have beene with their God, and how wonderfully their God has wrought for His ſervants and againſt His and their Adverſaries ever ſince they gained Briſtoll; Certainely
the Lord has wrought wonders for His people in every place ever ſince; He has wrought as marvellous things now in the North, and South, West alſo, as once He did, when He devided the ſea, and let the ranſomed paſſe-over: As marvailouſly has He protected, (ſeparated) here and there betwixt His friends and His enemies, as once He did betwixt the Iſraelites and the Egyptians, or betwixt David and Saul, And prayer did all this; It raiſed that SELAHAM MAHLEKOTH 1 Sam. 23. •• ., that rock of ſeparation, as once betwixt David and Saul, ſo now betwixt them, and their enemies. I muſt paſſe over that wonderfull worke of Providence towards Hull; There is a monument raiſed to the eternall memory of that ſalvation. I muſt leave every good man to his own collections; I know he has a booke wherein to regiſter the works of the Lord, and the operations of His hands, that he may muze on them; To theſe his collections, I will adde but this, which I received from an inhabitant in Gernſey; That, that monſter amongſt men, a Devill incarnate, that Abaddon, Apollyon, the Governour of the Caſtle there, a man indeed for ſhape, but an evening wolfe in practiſe; This bruitiſh man has diſcharged againſt the Towne 3000 ſhot of Ordnance from the Caſtle, and yet has deſtoyed neither man, woman nor child, only killed a Dog Oſburne has continued ſtorming that Town theſe 9 Moneths, yet has wounded only one Man, killed a Dogge, a Pigg, and a Pigeon., the loweſt and baſeſt creature in the world, yet better than man is when he has caſt-off his humanity. The ſumme of all is; Prayer and Praiſe (for that is alwayes included) has done all, that has been done; for God commands Prayer; and Prayer commands GOD; and GOD commands deliverance for His people; Praiſe ye the Lord. We have ſeene part of the wayes have been taken for the ſtrengthening the Kingdome; Prayers and Praiſes have done great things; Theſe have carried-forth the malignancy of the Kingdome: or obtained power againſt it. Theſe have brought-in all ſupplies from above, and commanded deliverances for Jacob. It is the Churches confidence for ever, that prayer, cloſing with a promiſe, offered-up in the hands of a Mediatour, will effect greater matters yet, than our eyes have ſeene, (i. e.) That there is no worke ſo difficult, no not reforming worke; No way ſo intricate, no not a Church-way, but prayer will make it poſſible and paſſible: (Aſſured,) That Jacob ſhall never be ſo ſmall, his affaires never ſo low, but prayer ſhall raiſe Jacob, a worme though he ſeeme to be; and pluck-up His affaires.
His ſeed never ſought God in vaine, from the firſt day of their ſeeking unto this day The 29 of March, a day to be written, whereon the Lord God gave His people a wonderfull returne of prayer, I ſay the Lord God, for though wee give as much honour as is ſitting to the chief, and all other inſtruments, yet to God all the glory. Joh. 14. 13, 15. 7. 1 Jo • . 8, 14.; It is their confidence, for the time to come, for they have a promiſe for it, Aske what you will and it ſhall be done. They will aske nothing but in reference and ſubmiſſion to their FATHERS will: and thence their confidence, that they are heard in whatſoever they aske; not for the dutiesſake (they abominate it as a duty only, and performed by themſelves) but for the promiſe-ſake, which the Lord will make good unto them for His Sons ſake, Amen. Prayer has a kind of omnipotency in it: Praiſe is an heavenly worke too and of the higheſt uſe: I would now gather ſome obſervations from what has beene ſaid touching both, then ile adde, what the Malignants have contributed hither, to the catalogue of our mercies, and matter of our praiſe, and ſo I ſhall conclude. The firſt obſervation is;

5. Now, at hearing of this newes, The Adverſary is-up on high, exceeding proud now; They ſet their mouth againſt Heaven, they ſpeake proudly now; And now the righteous, they are low, ſpeake as out of the duſt; They mourne unto their God: (Great cauſe they ſhould, becauſe they were ſo over joyed and confident in the arme of fleſh) They ſet their eyes ſtedfaſtly upon Him now, Who creates light and Peace (His light, His Peace is a creation, and this makes way to it) Their eye is ſingle now upon Gods arme; They had an eye and an eye before, an heart and a heart, more fixed upon the arme of fleſh than on the arme of God. O praiſed be God, Who has, by this ſtroake, made His ſervants eye ſingle now; And now they will pray fervently. Deliverance ſeems thruſt-back by the hand of violence, they will fetch it on-ward againe by their prayers: The time for their deliverance ſeemes ſtretched-out and lengthened; Luk. 22. 44. 
